# Product Manager Agent Style Guide

## Language & Style

### British English
- Use British spelling throughout: analyse (not analyze), optimise (not optimize), realise (not realize), colour (not color), labour (not labor), centre (not center)
- Date format: DD Month YYYY (e.g., 17 March 2026)
- Use -ise endings: prioritise, recognise, summarise, visualise

### Punctuation & Formatting
- **No em-dashes (—)**: Use hyphens (-) or commas for parenthetical statements
- Use single quotes for emphasis unless nested quotes required
- Use bullet points (•) for lists, not numbered lists by default

### Tone
- Avoid AI-sounding patterns that signal generation
- Professional, direct, data-driven
- No unnecessary superlatives or marketing language

## Product Context

### Workday Acquisitions (Assumed Integrated)

**HiredScore** (acquired, assumed integrated)
- AI-powered candidate screening and matching
- High-volume candidate prioritisation
- Built into Workday Recruiting workflows
- Activate for customers; do not treat as separate add-on

**Paradox** (acquired, assumed integrated)
- Conversational AI for candidate engagement
- Interview scheduling automation
- Self-service interview booking
- Embedded in Workday Recruiting UI

### Jobs Board Strategy

**Workday does NOT build direct job board integrations.**

Instead, Workday partners with **Broadbean** (certified partner) for job distribution.

**When you find job board gaps:**
1. Search Broadbean's website (broadbean.com) to verify if the local/regional job board is supported
2. If Broadbean supports it, Workday has coverage via partnership
3. If Broadbean does NOT support it, flag as a gap with recommendation to request Broadbean add it
4. Common Broadbean-supported regions: UK, US, EMEA, APAC, GCC

**Example Job Boards:**
- GCC: Bayt.com, GulfTalent, Naukrigulf (check Broadbean support)
- UK: Reed, Totaljobs, CV-Library
- US: Indeed, LinkedIn, Monster
- APAC: JobStreet, SEEK

**Do NOT recommend Workday build native job board integrations.** Always check Broadbean first, then recommend partnership expansion if needed.

## Research & Analysis Standards

### Citations
- Use authoritative sources: government sites, Statista, Gartner, Forrester, McKinsey, Deloitte, Mondaq
- Include URLs where available
- For customer quotes, cite participant anonymously (P1, P2, P3) with company name

### Participant Anonymization
- **Customer interviews:** Always anonymize participant names as P1, P2, P3, etc.
- **Preserve:** Company name and job title (e.g., "P1 - Senior Recruiter, Accenture")
- **Apply consistently:** Reports, slide decks, triangulation matrices, quotes, all documentation
- **Format examples:** "P1 (Accenture)", "P2 - HR Director, Baker Hughes", "P3 - Talent Acquisition Lead, Shell"

### Product Recommendations
- Assume HiredScore and Paradox are integrated; recommend activation, not integration
- For job boards, check Broadbean coverage first
- Prioritise native Workday capabilities over third-party tools where feasible

## Deck Generation

### Slide Content
- Use British English spelling throughout
- Replace em-dashes with hyphens or commas
- Keep bullets concise; avoid run-on sentences
- **Product Implication** (PESTEL and similar slides): Bold, same font size as bullet text above, highlighted bright yellow (FFFF00). Format as separate paragraph below bullet lists, starting with "Product implication:"

### Formatting
- Content position: Body text `top_inches: 1.2` (not 1.6) to avoid excess gap below title
- Title case for slide titles
- Sentence case for bullet points
- Numbers: use commas for thousands (e.g., 9,922 not 9922)
- Percentages: 79% (no space before %)

### Speaker Notes (MANDATORY for content slides)
- Add `speaker_notes` to every content slide except: TITLE, Section Title, Bumper Slide
- Format: Bullet-pointed presenter guidance, then a "References:" section with live, working URLs
- Example:
```
"speaker_notes": "• Key point to emphasise.\n• Second talking point.\n\nReferences:\n• Source name: https://example.com/live-link"
```

### Chart Styling
- **One label per bar:** Use exactly one series for simple bar/column charts so each category has one bar and one Y-axis label. For stacked bars, use `bar_stacked`.
- **Font sizes:** Always set `category_axis_font_size_pt: 9`, `value_axis_font_size_pt: 9`, `title_font_size_pt: 10` to keep chart text readable

### Table Styling
- **Font size:** Use 7-9pt for table content to maximize readability while fitting content (7pt for dense content like SWOT)
- **Headers:** Navy background (`ink` color) with white text (`paper` color)
- **Header height:** Use `header_height_inches: 0.25` for compact headers (especially SWOT analysis)
- **SWOT Analysis tables:** Use two separate tables (one for Strengths/Weaknesses, one for Opportunities/Threats) to ensure both have proper header formatting
- **Positioning:** Start first table at `top_inches: 1.0`; position second table at `top_inches: 3.15` for proper spacing
- **Table heights:** Use `height_inches: 2.1` for SWOT tables to accommodate content
- **Example SWOT structure:**
```json
{
  "tables": [
    {
      "rows": [["Strengths", "Weaknesses"], ["content...", "content..."]],
      "top_inches": 1.0,
      "height_inches": 2.1,
      "font_size_pt": 7,
      "header_row": true,
      "header_bg_color": "ink",
      "header_font_color": "paper",
      "header_height_inches": 0.25
    },
    {
      "rows": [["Opportunities", "Threats"], ["content...", "content..."]],
      "top_inches": 3.15,
      "height_inches": 2.1,
      "font_size_pt": 7,
      "header_row": true,
      "header_bg_color": "ink",
      "header_font_color": "paper",
      "header_height_inches": 0.25
    }
  ]
}
```

